Zest and quarter @lime{1}. Core, deseed, and dice @green bell pepper{1} into
½-inch pieces. Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%oz}, @sweet soy glaze{4%tbsp},
¼ cup water, @cornstarch{1%tsp}, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, and a squeeze of lime juice
to taste. (For 4 servings, use 1⁄3 cup water, 2 tsp cornstarch, and 1 tsp sugar.)

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high
heat. Add bell pepper; season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Cook,
stirring, until slightly tender, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @ground pork{10%oz} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned
and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir in sweet chili glaze; cook, stirring, until pork is coated, ~{30-60%seconds} more.

Meanwhile, gently massage @microwavable lemongrass brown rice{1} in package to
break up grains. Partially open package; place @butter{1%tbsp} inside. (For 4
servings, use 1 TBSP butter per package.) Microwave according to package
instructions, ~{90%seconds}.

Carefully open package fully; season rice with salt and pepper. Transfer to a
#medium bowl{} and add half the cilantro and lime zest to taste. Fluff with a
#fork{}.

Divide rice between bowls and top with pork and pepper mixture and remaining
cilantro. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> If you're looking for a quick and tasty weeknight meal, look no further!
> This one comes together in just 20 minutes. Ground pork and bell pepper are
> sautéed in a sweet chili sauce and served over buttery, zesty rice with a
> dash of cilantro. So when the kids have soccer practice, you're working extra
> late, or you just want to settle into your favorite side of the couch early:
> these bowls are here for you.